    name: 'Time Value of Money',
    category: 'Investment',
    subcategory: 'Investment Fundamentals',
    definition: 'The time value of money (TVM) is the concept that money available today is worth more than the same amount in the future due to its potential earning capacity. This core financial principle states that money can earn interest or investment returns, so a dollar today is worth more than a dollar tomorrow. TVM is the foundation for discounted cash flow analysis, net present value, and bond pricing.',
    simpleExplanation: 'A dollar today is worth more than a dollar in the future because you can invest today\'s dollar and it will grow. This is why people charge interest on loans.',
    example: 'If someone offers you ,000 today or ,000 in one year, take it today. You could invest the ,000 at 10% and have ,100 in one year. So ,000 today is equivalent to ,100 in one year at 10% return.',
    whyItMatters: 'TVM is the most fundamental concept in finance. Every financial decision - from stock valuation to retirement planning to capital budgeting - depends on TVM. Without understanding TVM, it is impossible to make rational financial decisions.',
    relatedTerms: ['net-present-value', 'discount-rate', 'future-value', 'present-value', 'compound-interest'],
    interviewQuestions: ['What is the time value of money?', 'How do you calculate present value?', 'What is the relationship between discount rates and present value?', 'How does TVM apply to stock valuation?', 'What are the five variables in TVM calculations?'],
    sharkTankExample: 'When Kevin O\'Leary demands a  annual royalty instead of  upfront, he is applying TVM. He believes the stream of future payments will be worth more than the lump sum because the business will grow, making future royalties larger.',
    realCompanyExample: 'Amazon\'s decision to reinvest profits rather than pay dividends is a TVM-based strategy. Jeff Bezos argued that reinvesting in growth creates more value for shareholders than paying dividends today. Amazon\'s stock price growth from .73 (1997 IPO) to ,000+ proves the power of reinvesting today\'s money for future growth.',
    faqs: [{ question: 'What is the present value of money?', answer: 'The current value of a future sum of money, discounted at a specific rate. PV = FV / (1 + r)^n.' }, { question: 'What is future value?', answer: 'The value of a current asset at a future date based on an assumed growth rate. FV = PV x (1 + r)^n.' }, { question: 'What is a discount rate?', answer: 'The interest rate used to calculate present value. It represents the opportunity cost of capital.' }, { question: 'How does inflation affect TVM?', answer: 'Inflation reduces purchasing power over time, making future money worth less. Real returns must account for inflation.' }, { question: 'What is an annuity in TVM?', answer: 'A series of equal payments at regular intervals. TVM calculates the present or future value of the entire stream.' }],
    references: ['Brealey, R. A., Myers, S. C., & Allen, F. (2020). Principles of Corporate Finance.', 'Bodie, Z., Kane, A., & Marcus, A. J. (2021). Investments.', 'Damodaran, A. (2012). Investment Valuation.', 'Fabozzi, F. J. (2015). Bond Markets, Analysis, and Strategies.', 'Ross, S. A., Westerfield, R. W., & Jordan, B. D. (2019). Fundamentals of Corporate Finance.'],
