    subcategory: 'Economic Concepts',
    definition: 'Inflation is the rate at which the general level of prices for goods and services rises over time, eroding purchasing power. It is measured by indices such as the Consumer Price Index (CPI) and Producer Price Index (PPI). Moderate inflation is considered healthy for an economy, but high inflation can destabilize markets and reduce real investment returns.',
    simpleExplanation: 'Inflation means things get more expensive over time. Your  buys less next year than it does today because prices keep going up.',
    example: 'In 1980, a gallon of milk cost .65. By 2025, the same milk costs approximately .50. This 173% price increase over 45 years represents an average annual inflation rate of about 2.3%. Your dollar buys less than half of what it did in 1980.',
    whyItMatters: 'Inflation directly impacts investment returns, purchasing power, and financial planning. Investors must earn returns above inflation to maintain purchasing power. Inflation expectations influence interest rates, stock valuations, and asset allocation decisions.',
    relatedTerms: ['deflation', 'consumer-price-index', 'real-return', 'nominal-return', 'monetary-policy'],
    interviewQuestions: ['What is inflation and how is it measured?', 'What causes inflation?', 'How does inflation affect investments?', 'What is the difference between nominal and real returns?', 'What assets perform well during inflation?'],
